nce in the classroom challenged the status quo, forcing educators, students, and communities to confront deeply ingrained prejudices.</p>\n<p>The experience also highlighted the psychological and social challenges faced by Black students entering segregated schools. Ruby was the only student in her class for an entire year due to white parents withdrawing their children in protest. This isolation underscores the systemic barriers to equality that desegregation efforts sought to dismantle.</p>\n<h2>Key Fast Facts About Ruby Bridges</h2>\n<p>To appreciate the breadth of Ruby Bridges’ influence, here are essential fast facts about Ruby Bridges that shed light on her historic role and legacy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Age at Integration:</strong> Ruby was six years old when she first attended William Frantz Elementary School.</li>\n<li><strong>Date:</strong> November 14, 1960, marked her first day at the integrated school.</li>\n<li><strong>Protection Detail:</strong> She was escorted by four U.S. federal marshals due to threats and protests.</li>\n<li><strong>Educational Context:</strong> She was the first African American child to attend an all-white elementary school in New Orleans.</li>\n<li><strong>Teacher:</strong> Barbara Henry, a Boston native, was the only teacher willing to educate Ruby in an otherwise empty classroom.</li>\n<li><strong>Community Resistance:</strong> Many white families pulled their children out of school in protest of integration.</li>\n<li><strong>Legacy:</strong> Ruby Bridges’ bravery has been commemorated in art, literature, and education, inspiring generations.</li>\n<li><strong>Ongoing Activism:</strong> Ruby later established the Ruby Bridges Foundation to promote tolerance and equal rights.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Ruby Bridges and Cultural Representation</h3>\n<p>Ruby Bridges’ story has transcended historical texts, entering popular culture and education as a symbol of resilience. Norman Rockwell’s famous painting, “The Problem We All Live With,